version.name: Wolf Mail
version.description: International musician Wolf Mail was awarded "best blues guitarist" in 2005 by Japan's Guitar Player magazine. Bust out your leather jacket, pull your pants up high and sit back as Mail transports you back into the fifties with his award winning music.

event.name: Finoa Joy Hawkins and Blue Dream

version.name: Finoa Joy Hawkins and Blue Dream
version.description: Award winning Pianist Fiona Joy Hawkins is known for her soothing contemporary classical works. The Aria nominee is joined by Blue Dream, a collective of improvisational musicians who helps bring Hawkins music to life.

version.name: Lil' Band O Gold
version.description: Swamp dogs and blues boys unite in this all star band of highly accomplished musicians from the southern states of the USA. The coming together of this magical group was captured in the acclaimed documentary, ‘The Promised Land’ which has been re-pressed due to popular demand. Following their reception at the East Coast Blues and Roots Festival these lads are back for another bite at the cherry with 2 shows in Sydney.

version.name: Lil' Band O' Gold
version.description: The Louisiana super group are returning for shows all over the country including their first appearance in Sydney.

event.name: Woodlands: Simon Tedeschi and Kevin Hunt

version.name: Woodlands: Simon Tedeschi and Kevin Hunt
version.description: Pianists Simon Tedeschi and Kevin Hunt play tracks from their new ABC Jazz CD Woodlands, an enticing mix of Classical, Jazz and improvisations on original compositions and well-loved audience favourites.

version.name: Paul Dempsey
version.description: As an offshoot of his tour with Powderfinger, Paul Dempsey has added some solo, acoustic shows in Sydney and Melbourne. The Something For Kate frontman's debut solo album Everything is True was nominated for 3 Arias and won iTunes Australian Album of the Year. If floppy haired, whisky voiced, singer-songwriters are your style then Paul Dempsey just may be your god.

version.name: Dan Kelly
version.description: It has been a long wait but Dan Kelly has finally released his solo album, Dan Kelly's Dream, and is now setting out on a massive national tour. Head to the Annandale and catch the insightful yet kooky lyricism of Dan Kelly as he tries to make music, entertain the masses and save the planet, all at once.

version.name: Baroness
version.description: They're here on support duties for Metallica, but since they've not long released their second disc The Blue Album, Baroness want to show off their metal chops in this headline sideshow.

version.name: Diesel
version.description: There once was a man with 7 guitars. His name was Diesel. He couldn't choose between his guitars so he decided that he would do a national tour and play them all. With 7 guitars helping to chronicle his musical journey up until the present this will be a show with many song, many strings, and a plectrum or two.

version.name: Jonneine Zapata
version.description: With endless comparisons to Jim Morrison and PJ Harvey, Jonneine Zapata grabs you by the neck and drags you into her dark undercurrent, and now Bringing the sounds of the LA underground to Sydney for the first time.

version.name: Bedouin Soundclash
version.description: if you knew nothing about Bedouin Soundclash in a first listening you could swear that this was the kind of Reggae that could only come straight from Kingston, as opposed to the wintery Mountie harboring nation they're actually from. Currently on the international touring circuit Bedouin Soundclash sound like coconuts, sand and cool island breezes all mix in some sort of sonic blender.

event.name: The Three Up Tour featuring Illy, 360 and Skryptcha

version.name: The Three Up Tour featuring Illy, 360 and Skryptcha
version.description: Three Up Tour brings together three of the hottest emcees out there, with Illy, 360 and Skryptcha set to tear the stage down. Each rapper has a different style and flow, so every punter will be pleased. Watch some of the best do their thing at the Annandale, the unofficial home of Aussie hip hop.

version.name: Peabody
version.description: Thirteen years after first strutting onto the Annandale stage Peabody are back, with a new album, 'Loose Manifesto' which looks at the modern day through Peabody's unique perspective.

version.name: SKA Weekender Round 2
version.description:
The opening night of this weekend long Ska Festival will be held at the Annandale Hotel on the Saturday with sets by Area 7, Dan Potthast, The Real Deal, The My Ty’s, Steel City Allstars, Loonee Tunes, Chris Duke and the Royals, Hightime, and the Alpacaccinos.
The Sunday covers cruise will feature Area 7 performing their album "Bitter and Twisted” from start to finish, Los Capitanes performing Sublime’s “Self Titled” and Backyskank performing as “Complete Madness”.
The After party for the cruise will be held at the Town Hall Hotel in Newtown and will see Dan Potthast, The Real Deal and Cohen Heart performing kicking off at 6pm.
You can purchase tickets to one, two or all three events, it all depends on how much Ska you can handle?

version.name: Holly Throsby & the Hello Tigers
version.description: She's back, Sydney, with a new single ('Here Is My Co-Pilot') and a new backing band, awesomely called the Hello Tigers, all leading up to the imminent release of her forthcoming album Team.

version.name: GBH and The Rumjacks
version.description: There isn't a self-respecting gutter punk, hardcore kid or subcultural miscreant alive who hasn't seen the GBH logo emblazoned on the back of a leather jacket, a denim vest, or a torn-up t-shirt.

version.name: Shihad
version.description: A national tour promoting their new album, Ignite.

version.name: GBH with Rumjacks
version.description: Formed in 1978, this English hardcore punk band has still got it.

version.name: The Holidays
version.description: The Holidays' debut album, Post Paradise, has been a long time coming.

version.name: Guttermouth
version.description: The infamously controversial American punk rock band returns to Australian shores.

version.name: Kiwi Soundz
version.description: New Zealand's Ardijah 1814 Ruia Aperahama and Maisey Rika take the stage in support of the Sydney Marae Appeal.

version.name: Bone Thugs-N-Harmony
version.description: The enduring hip-hop legends return with a new album - Uni-5: The World's Enemy - and an accompanying tour that promises to include all the hits. Which is very accomodating of them, really.

version.name: The Field
version.description: Stockholm's The Field - aka Axel Willner - bring blissed-out ambient-shoegaze electronica to Australia for the first time in support of last year's Yesterday & Today.

version.name: El Guincho
version.description: Everyone's favourite Barcelona laptop electonica whizzkid is back in our nation for a run of festivals and doing this one sideshow while he's about.

version.name: Parades and Ernest Ellis
version.description: The Gaelic presents two of the next big indie acts, with Parades and Ernest Ellis taking the stage in one night. Parades are celebrating their debut album, while Ernest Ellis performed at Splendour this year. Now they're together, for your viewing pleasure.

version.name: Rufio and Mest
version.description: Straight out of LA comes Rufio, on the back of their album Anybody Out There. A record packed with big guitars and bigger hooks, their high energy show will have you jumping. Rufio is joined by Mest.

version.name: Trashed MILF
version.description: Bands, performers and DJs blast indie/rock across two rooms of drunken sleaze. Get there early to catch happy hour from 8pm till 9.30.

version.name: Afghanistan: The Perils of Freedom 1993-2009
version.description: Between 1993 and 2009, Stephen Dupont documented the conflict-ridden country of Afghanistan. This major new exhibition presents a confronting portrait of a country that has remained a focal point of the world’s attention for several decades.

version.name: Nikon-Walkley Photographic Exhibition
version.description: Discover the finalist in this year's prestigious Walkley Awards for photography.

version.name: Leon Kossoff
version.description: Charcoal sketches of paintings.

version.name: Streetscape Animation
version.description: Watch the development of a large-scale chalk drawn animation, as a new figure drawing is added to the outside wall of Firstdraft Depot every second day of Art and About 2010.

version.name: Comedy on the Rox
version.description: Check out round three of the Quest for the Best Preliminary Final which pits young/not so young comedians against each other in a gladiatorial style battle for a $5000 prize and untold glory.

event.name: Full Body Contact No Love Tennis

version.name: Full Body Contact No Love Tennis
version.description: Tuesday means improv at the Rox with the Tennis team!

version.name: Mic In Hand
version.description: Open mic at its finest with a top-notch headliner and a class MC every week.

version.name: As You Like It
version.description: The Forest of Arden: Orlando loves Rosalind. Rosalind is disguised as a boy called Ganymede. Phebe loves Ganymede. Silvius loves Phebe. Rosalind loves Orlando back. Oliver is hunting Orlando. Celia loves Oliver. Celia is disguised as Aliena. The Duke is hunting Celia. The other Duke is hunting deer. Jaques loves the deer. Touchstone is freaked out by Jaques. Audrey loves Touchstone. Touchstone loves words... It turns out to be quite a hard play to describe. In the end there's a wedding and they all go home.Eamon Flack is the genius that had the bright idea of staging A Midsummer Night's Dream in the tiny Downstairs Theatre in 2009 (and, for something completely different, Beckett's moody The End in 2010). He is, as such, the perfect choice to direct As You Like It, one of Shakespeare's loopier rom coms - the play that gave the world Shakespeare's 'Seven Ages of Man' speech. In the cast, Charlie Garber and Gareth Davies, who took turns stealing the show from the cast and each other in that aforementioned Midsummer Night, will be joined by Alison Bell (The Promise, Rabbit... best not mention that ABC2 programme she did) and Shelly Lauman.

version.name: The Sweetest Thing
version.description: The premier of this new Australian work, a story of a grieving family seen through the fram of chaos theory.

version.name: A Distressing Scenario
version.description: A double bill of devised pieces Everything I Know About the Global Financial Crisis in One Hour and The Market Is Not Functioning. The night will examine the cultural repercussions of the current economic state.

version.name: Summer of the Seventeenth Doll
version.description: Every summer, Barney and Roo have come back from the Queensland canefields to the Carlton house they share with Nancy and Olive for their annual season of leisure. This year though, Nancy's gone and got married, and Pearl's taking her place..."After 17 years as artistic director at Belvoir," the season brochure tells us, "Neil Armfield directs the play about how, after 17 years, all good things must come to an end." Summer of the Seventeenth Doll is an absolute classic of the Australian stage - if you haven't seen it, chances are you've studied it - and Armfield, as the brochure hints, will be in a unique position to tell a story about change: the pain, the excitement, and the danger of fighting it. The production will feature the singular talents of actors Dan Wyllie - you will surely have seen him on stage in The Pillowman and Cloudstreet, or on screen in Love My Way and Underbelly - and Robyn Nevin. That's right: two separate Robyn Nevin performances on the same stage in a matter of months.

version.name: The Diary of a Madman
version.description: In a revival of their 1989 collaboration, Neil Armfield directs Geoffrey Rush as Poprishin, one of millions of clerks in St Petersburg in the time of the Czar, who is convinced he is on his way to the top.

version.name: The Seagull
version.description: The Seagull is Chekhov's extraordinary gathering of a group of bruised and incandescent dreamers who cannot, no matter how they try, get what they want. It's also one of the masterpieces of theatre about theatre, an exploration of how telling stories and coining symbols interacts with life. By turns elevated and scrappy, gorgeous and mundane, The Seagull is a vision of humanity enduring in the presence of eternity.The visionary director of Company B's Measure for Measure and STC's War of the Roses, Benedict Andrews, is a man whose very name tends to strike equal parts terror and excitement in the hearts of most Sydney theatregoers. Here he'll be turning his fierce imagination and steely gaze (take a look at his headshot in the theatre programmes - the man doesn't sleep) to another champion of new theatrical experiences, Anton Chekhov (Uncle Vanya). The Seagull is a play about love, in all its guises, and a "masterpiece of theatre about theatre". It's a terrific all-star cast: Maeve Dermody, John Gaden, Gareth Davies, Emily Barclay and, back on the boards at last, the legendary Judy Davis.

version.name: The Wild Duck
version.description: Hjalmar Ekdal's father was rich until scandal cast the family into poverty. Now he lives in a tiny flat with his father, his wife Gina, his daughter Hedvig and a duck. And there's about to be a new member of the household. Gregers Werle is an idealist who has been living on a mountaintop for the last 15 years and he has just returned to town with a secret that could shatter the little world Hjalmar has built around himself.The Wild Duck is an intricate study of family life from that master dramatist of family life, Henrik Ibsen. The production will star a couple of our favourite Sydney thespians: two of the Three Blind Mice, Toby Schmitz and Ewen Leslie. (The third blind mouse is conspicuously absent.) It's to be directed by Simon Stone, who Ralph Myers calls "the hottest young director in the country in inverted commas". Earlier this year Stone directed The Promise, also in the Upstairs Theatre and starring Ewen Leslie. Last year he adapted Ibsen's 1894 drama Little Eyolf into The Only Child, a bold production - full of emotional and physical nakedness - in which most of the action happened in a bathtub.

version.name: Jack Charles v the Crown
version.description: From Stolen Generation to Koori theatre in the 70s, from film sets to Her Majesty's prisons, Jack Charles v the Crown runs the gamut of a life lived to its utmost. Charles's unswerving optimism transforms this tale of addiction, crime and doing time into a kind of vagabond's progress - a map of the traps of dispossession and a guide to reaching the age of grey-haired wisdom.Star of The Chant of Jimmie Blacksmith, Koori elder, founder of the first Aboriginal theatre company and former heroin addict - Jack Charles has a heck of a story to tell. Part of it was told in Bastardy, a 1972 play by John Romeril; part of it was told in the confronting documentary of a few years ago, also called Bastardy, which followed Charles for seven years. Uncle Jack Charles v the Crown is the next chapter, as told by Jack Charles himself, with playwright John Romeril back to lend a guiding hand on the script. The one-man show will be directed by Torres Strait Islander Rachael Maza Long.

version.name: The Business
version.description: Our central character is a woman who grew up poor, clawed her way out, and built an empire in the outer suburbs. But her salad days in middle Australia are under threat. The world is accelerating into the future, her husband is on his last legs, and the kids smell blood. Now is the time for a spectacular generational showdown over who gets the prize.Cristabel Sved directed the recent production of Parlour Song and Martin McDonagh's brutally funny Beauty Queen of Leenane; Jonathan Gavin wrote Bang!, a mighty play that went off in the Downstairs Theatre in June 2010. Together, they've come up with a new translation of Maxim Gorky's portrait of a dysfunctional family, The Business, re-setting it in politically incorrect 1980s Australia. In Sved's words, it's a wild, dark comedy that threatens to turn into a farce or melodrama at any moment. It stars Sarah Peirse, who made a knockout Home Secretary in 2009's Gethsemane.

version.name: Neighbourhood Watch
version.description: And God said: Thou shalt love thy neighbour. He obviously hadn't reckoned on Eva. Eva is a battle-hardened Hungarian-Australian veteran of the twentieth century. Catherine is her neighbour: twenty-something and waiting for a better world. The question is, will their unlikely friendship outlive the colossal forces of history, the inevitability of death, and a trip to the mall to see Mamma Mia?Playwright Lally Katz hopefully won't mind us saying that she is a mad woman. She brought a female Frankenstein to the stage, collaborated with Hilary Bell on the magical The Mysteries: Genesis and dreamed up one of the more frightening creations to take the stage in recent years, the Apocalypse Bear. Neighbourhood Watch is her latest play, with a part performed by, and written specifically for, the wonderful Robyn Nevin (last seen as the drifting matriarch in Long Day's Journey into Night). It's the product of the two years Katz spent with a real-life Eva - talking to her, cleaning out her birdcage, that kind of thing. Nevin urged Katz to write a part for her that was "tough and funny" - Neighbourhood Watch will surely be both.

version.name: Human Interest Story
version.description: Our world is saturated with news. Torrents of information transport us from battlefields to crime scenes, from celebrity homes to our own backyards. But how does this unending flow of information shape us?Human Interest Story had its debut at Melbourne's Malthouse Theatre in July 2010. It is, in Myers' words, "not a play but a piece of theatre" that finds its inspiration from a most unlikely source: news, current affairs and the mass media. It's the brainchild of Lucy Guerin, and takes place in a set designed by Guerin's partner, Gideon Obarzanek, who masterminded the dance/light show Mortal Engine that played Sydney Theatre earlier in the year. It's a dance work with a sense of fun and a sense of humour, featuring - how many dance works can you say this about? - a special newscast from SBS newsreader Anton Enus.

version.name: Cut
version.description: A mash up fantasy and reality, thought and action in a one-woman show.

version.name: The Kiss
version.description: An ambitious word-for-word staging of four short stories (all called 'The Kiss') that takes a leaf out of the book of Gatz, the Sydney Festival 2009 hit that staged The Great Gatsby in its entirety.

version.name: Windmill Baby
version.description: Windmill Baby is the story of Black Australians in the service of White Australia - and a love story.

event.name: And They Called Him Mr Glamour

version.name: And They Called Him Mr Glamour
version.description: And They Called Him Mr Glmaour is Davies' one-man show that sounds like the result of his descent into madness.

version.name: The Dark Room
version.description: A time-warping thriller that will mark Brendan Cowell's first-ever performance on a Belvoir stage.

version.name: Fame - The Musical
version.description: FAME – The Musical is the story of a diverse group of students at New York City’s celebrated High School of the Performing Arts. Meet the class of 2010 in this new production.

version.name: Tap Dogs
version.description: Winner of 11 major international awards including an Olivier for Best Choreography, Tap Dogs arrives at the Capitol Theatre this summer.

event.name: Last of the Red Hot Lovers

version.name: Last of the Red Hot Lovers
version.description: Sensible Barney Cashman, 47, longs to do something wild and so embarks on three seductions in Neil Simon's famous comedy.

version.name: Wish I'd Said That
version.description: An insightful one-man show centered upon one man, his passion for performance, and his struggle to form a tangible bond with his daughter.

version.name: Lotte's Gift
version.description: A touching recollection of memoirs, memories and the relationship between grandmother and granddaughter.

event.name: Peace Train - The Cat Stevens Story

version.name: Peace Train - The Cat Stevens Story
version.description: Enjoy live performances from the Firecats as they and Darren Coggan explore the man behind the music.

version.name: List Operators
version.description: Recently nominated for 'Best Show' at the 2010 Melbourne International Comedy Festival, the List Operators bring their child-friendly show to Sydney. Involving farts and silly fun, this show is sure to bring out the kid in anyone.

version.name: Glow
version.description: Latest in interactive video technologies are utilised in this dance performance to generate a digital landscape in which a lone being mutates in and out of human form. The video tracking system enhances and is manipulated by the gestures of the dancers.

event.name: A Day in the Death of Joe Egg

version.name: A Day in the Death of Joe Egg
version.description: Brian and Sheila, a young married couple, care for their daughter, 'Joe Egg'. They face adversity with bravery and laughter, but something lies beneath the antics. This thought-provoking and funny play is described by London's National Theatre as one of the most significant of the 20th Century.

version.name: The List Operators for Kids
version.description: Silly sound effects, practical jokes and a brand new fart machine feature in this messy and anarchic sketch comedy show for kids. It even comes with the guarantee to be more fun than a Wii.

event.name: The Chronic Ills of Robert Zimmerman: AKA Bob Dylan (A Lie)

version.name: The Chronic Ills of Robert Zimmerman: AKA Bob Dylan (A Lie)
version.description: This hit of the Adelaide Fringe Festival returns for an encore run as part of Best of Independent Theatre, it is an irreverent homage to the legendary Bob Dylan.

version.name: A Solitary Choice
version.description: Direct from an acclaimed performance at the Edinburgh Fringe Festival, Tamara Lee's solo performance is the story of a difficult decision after a passionate affair.

version.name: The Hole Thing
version.description: Back by popular demand, The Hole Thing asks you to unleash your inner photographer and take part in a unique competition that proved a hit in Art & About 2009. Discover how to use a pinhole camera made from cardboard, then choose a subject in postal code 2010, Darlinghurst and Surry Hills to enter.

version.name: Esperanza - Taking Action
version.description: Esperanza - Taking Action documents the activities of volunteer Greenpeace activists last year blockading two coal export terminals in Queensland.

version.name: Quite simply Spain
version.description: An utterly Iberian experience with plenty of pinchos and a range of Spanish wines.

version.name: The Great houses of Champagne
version.description: Tonight is about Champagne. Bottles have been sourced and selected from six of the great houses of the French region and are presented at Balzac to compliment a five-course menu. Matt Kemp and Guy Collins bring you this event unique to the Sydney International Food Festival. There will be canapes as well ...and did I mention Champagne?

version.name: Royal kitchens of India
version.description: Eat like a Maharajah (or a Maharani) at Nilgiri's all-you-can-eat buffet during the Sydney International Food Festival. Bookings are essential to grab a spot at the feast typical to regal Indian tradition. We're talking pure spicy indulgence here...and a mass exploitation of all your senses.

version.name: Chatpate Chaat aur Rangili Lassiyan
version.description:
Mumbai's Chowpatty beach, famous for its serving of tasty Indian snacks from street vendors is coming to Nilgiri's.
Be transported, via palette, to this part of the world with authentic snacks including pav bhaji, pani puri, ragda patties and chana zor garam. Lassis will be served to compliment. Sweet or salty - these yoghurty drinks are just heavenly and curiously go oh so well with the savoury.
What may sound like complete gibberish is what characterises this utterly unique evening of Indian delight... and if Nilgiri gets it right these snacks are very, very yummy.
Bookings essential.

event.name: What's Inside the Bug Man's Box?

version.name: What's Inside the Bug Man's Box?
version.description: Bug Man Stephen Fellenberg showcases all kinds of insects, from spiders to scorpions, and brings along his own personal collection for a creepy crawly show 'n' tell.

version.name: Christmas Dinner Cooking Class
version.description: Lucio's chef Logan Campbell offers tips for this year's Christmas dinner, Italian style.

version.name: The Engine Room
version.description: Meet some of Sydney's most exciting designers and see their work spaces in this open studios program organised by Object Gallery.

event.name: Margaret Mead Festival - River Of No Return

version.name: Margaret Mead Festival - River Of No Return
version.description: This documentary follows actress Frances Daingangan on her journey from Arnhem Land to the red carpet. Featuring a Q&A session with director Darlene Johnson

version.name: Margaret Mead Festival - Cooking History
version.description: Cooking History examines the world of food in battle, as various army cooks recall their experiences in front-line kitchens.

version.name: Margaret Mead Festival - Hotel Sahara
version.description: In a small town on the edge of the ocean and the Sahara, refugees wait to cross illegally into Europe. This documentary looks into what motivates people to flee their home countries.

version.name: Margaret Mead Festival - The Living
version.description: Sergiy Bukovsky's documentary focuses on the Ukraine, a country shattered by years of communist oppression, in particular the survivors of the 1932 forced famine.

version.name: Iain Banks - Author Event
version.description: Science-fiction author Iain Banks talks to book reviewer George Williams via Skype about his new book, Surface Detail.

version.name: Peter Lloyd - Author Event
version.description: Distinguished ABC foreign correspondent Peter Lloyd was arrested and put in gaol in Singapore in 2008. To cope with the highly publicised, extremely traumatic ordeal, he decided to enter with the approach of a seasoned journalist on an assignment. He wrote a book called 'Inside Story' detailing his astonishing story; come with questions.

version.name: Dimitris Vardoulakis - Author Event
version.description: Vardoulakis' book 'The Doppelgänger' presents the subject in title as literature's response to the philosophical focus on subjectivity, and extends his theory to explore the idea that literature is philosophy's double.

version.name: Paul Kelly - Special Event
version.description: This could be as close to realising the 'if you could have the perfect dinner party' fantasy for Paul Kelly fans as possible. Talking to Sydney Morning Herald music writer Bernard Zuel about his memoir 'How to Make Gravy,' get in quick for this one.

version.name: Woollahra Small Sculpture Prize 2010
version.description: The Small Sculpture Prize celebrates its tenth year. A broad exhibition of the finalists assures that this art form is well and truly alive in Australia.

version.name: Hugh Mackay - Author's Talk
version.description: Social researcher, psychologist and writer Hugh Mackay returns with his new book, 'What Makes Us Tick?' He will talk about the book's highly personal account drawn from his extensive research into individual Australians. Bookings essential.

version.name: Janelle Bloom - Book Talk
version.description: Janelle Bloom is a cook, recipe writer, food editor and stylist who appears on the popular cooking show 'Ready, Steady, Cook'. Her new book, 'Family Food & Weekend Feasts' features her favourite recipes. Morning tea with Janelle will give an insight into these fabulous recipes. Entry includes a coffee and handmade chocolate plus nibbles prepared by Janelle.

version.name: Shaun Micallef - Book Talk
version.description: Well-known Australian comedian, Shaun Micallef from shows such as 'Full Frontal', 'Newstopia' and 'Talkin' 'Bout Your Generation', has turned his skills to novel writing. 'Preincarnate' is a genre bending, fast paced adventure through time. Be sure to have a fun evening with the multi-talented Shaun Micallef.

version.name: Kate Morton - Book Talk
version.description: Kate Morton, the bestselling author of 'The Shifting Fog' and 'The Forgotten Garden' returns with her third novel, 'The Distant Hours'. Help uncover the mysteries within her books at a talk with Kate.

version.name: Make a Wimpy Kid Diary
version.description: Handmade books and pens are provided so you can make your own 'Wimpy Kid' diary (from the book series and film). The ticket also gives you a $5 discount off a 'Wimpy Kid' title. Bookings essential.

version.name: 4 Faces of Love
version.description: Love is in the air with an amorous dinner-and-show combo: enjoy a three course meal while viewing a programme of four love-inspired plays that explore themes from filial affection to single ladies' dilemmas.

version.name: Evidence & DJ Total Eclipse
version.description: Hip hop heads best get excited as Dilated People’s frontman MC Evidence is heading down to Sydney with none other than Total Eclipse from the Xecutioners on the ones and twos.

version.name: Harbour Party 2010
version.description: The first announcement for the city's most girt-by-sea new year's party with Digitalism, Sneaky Sound System, Dennis Ferrer, Riva Starr and Goodwill.

version.name: Thrill the World
version.description: Start learning the dance moves because once again Thrill the World will be making the world record attempt for the most people performing the zombie dance from Michael Jackson's Thriller music video.

version.name: Craig Scott
version.description: This week Jazz in the Cafe presents Craig Scott.

version.name: The Pigeons
version.description: The latest Griffin production will make you think - it's certainly required a lot of thought from director Sarah Giles and her courageous cast. Written by Berlin playwright David Gieselmann and newly translated by Maja Zade, scenes in The Pigeons run simultaneously, side-by-side - and the actors are onstage at all times. We spoke to Giles about making it all work.What immediately struck you reading the script for The Pigeons?Two things. The first is that the form is really exciting: it's one of those plays that reflects the modern world in the way that it is written. It's not like you walk in and see a linear play from start to finish.The second thing is: I just ‘got' it. For me it's about the struggle between obligation and desire and the things we want in life we can't get. Modern life ties us down and stops us from pursuing the things we want. The central character is this guy who's got everything that should make him happy - but he has these plans to disappear.How do you deal with the technical form of this play as a director?To look at it on the page, it seems quite broken up, but it is truly one long continuous scene. It has a real flow to it that you almost wouldn't expect when reading it on the page. It's a huge challenge for actors. They've got about eight balls in the air. They need to know what their focus is and they also need to be listening out peripherally for what's going on one foot away from them.But you are in fact staging the scenes. Yes, you'll walk in to the world and you'll see a room and you'll see eight people and it'll look completely real. One of the things that Gieselmann is trying to get to the audience to is try and stop and take a second look. There's this great quote from Lilly Allen [in the script]: "When you look with your eyes everything seems nice / but if you look twice you can see it's all lies". We're trying to get the audience to interrogate things a bit more and pay a bit more attention, because you can go through your entire life not really looking at someone or not really engaging.The play was written in Berlin - one always hears that the German humour is not so dissimilar from our own. Have you found that the comedy translates well?It's a very unusual sense of humour but one that Australians will get. You've got these eight characters - and the audience will go along and relate to at least one of these people. There is a broad range of comedy that comes out through all the different characters. When I had a chat to [playwright David Gieselmann], he said that he writes a lot of comedy and they do far better over seas than in Germany. Perhaps other cultures have an ability to laugh more than in Germany. Darryn King

version.name: For a Better World
version.description: Set in an isolated jungle, sometime in the future, this play intricately explores the concepts of war, gender, aggression and power, while maintaining a modern relevance.

version.name: Speaking in Tongues
version.description: Two unhappily married couples inadvertently switch partners; a man mourns a lost love; a woman goes missing... Stories intersect, overlap and entwine in Andrew Bovell's Speaking in Tongues a genuine ‘Griffin classic' that premiered at the SBW Stables Theatre 15 years ago. It was the basis of Ray Lawrence's film Lantana, also written by Bovell, starring Geoffrey Rush and Anthony LaPaglia. Like Bovell's recent When the Rain Stops Falling, Speaking in Tongues is a challenging, veritable hall of mirrors of a play – and Griffin artistic director Sam Strong, who last guided audiences through the complexities of the GFC in The Power of Yes, is just the man for the job.

version.name: Silent Disco
version.description: Tamara and Jasyn, a girl and a guy - in Year 10 and hot for each other. What could be simpler? Except things aren't simple at all: school's a downer, Tamara and Jasyn's family lives are anything but normal, and relationships aren't so easy when there's no-one to tell you how to do it. Silent Disco, winner of the 2009 Griffin Award, will be a co-production with the Australian Theatre for Young People - so it's just as well it has a playwright and director who ‘get' young people. Playwright Lachlan Philpott is currently the director of ATYP's Fresh Ink programme – judging by a quick squiz at the mostly capital letter-eschewing script, he's got the voice of teen angst just right – and director Lee Lewis, as well as having taught at ATYP, Sydney Uni and NIDA, was the director of the NSW State Schools Senior Drama Ensemble for three years. (Note: A 'silent disco' is when everyone dances to music on his or her own pair of headphones. It's one way to have a dance party and not disrupt the neighbours – and, I'm just putting it out there, maybe a metaphor for isolation and alienation. Time Out has it on good authority that Griffin is considering holding an actual silent disco event.)

event.name: And No More Shall We Part

version.name: And No More Shall We Part
version.description: A terminal illness threatens to bring about a tragic end to a thirty-year marriage. An aged couple prepare to face the crisis - and their mortality - on their own terms. First performed at the 2009 Melbourne Fringe Festival, And No More Shall We Part gets its name, we presume, from a particularly heartbreaking Nick Cave lyric: " And no more shall we part / It will no longer be necessary / And no more will I say, dear heart / I am alone and she has left me." (Visit Song Meanings for lively discussion about whether or not the track is actually about a murder-suicide.) The play itself is a silence-filled meditation on love, marriage, saying goodbye, and, yes, assisted suicide from Tom Holloway, the Tasmanian playwright behind such poignant works as Beyond the Neck and Love Me Tender. The production will reunite Holloway and Sam Strong, whose production of Holloway's Red Sky Morning garnered considerable acclaim and toured nationally. And No More Shall We Part won an AWGIE and the Melbourne Dramatists' New Writing Award – for which Holloway was presented $250 and opening night tickets to Melbourne Theatre Company performances all year(!).

version.name: This Years Ashes
version.description: Ellen lives a shiny life in the heart of a shiny city. She hates her office job, the alcohol isn't making her as drunk as it used to, and she seems to be allergic to the water. But there is always the company of strangers in this city - the stranger, the better. This Year's Ashes is a brand new play from NIDA's Head of Playwriting, playwright in her own right and one-time rock climbing instructor Jane Bodie. It's an examination of a relationship – and cricket – that, our sources tell us, ought to be dubbed a ‘reluctant rom com' which will both satisfy and subvert the rom com genre. The production reunites director Shannon Murphy and actor Belinda Bromilow, the duo who worked magic together on My Name is Rachel Corrie. (And, speaking of cricket, Nimrod Street just might see a bit of laneway cricket action next year as part of Griffin's commitment to inspired extracurricular events. Stay tuned.)

version.name: The Ugly One
version.description: A slick, black satire from Berlin playwright and frequent Benedict Andrews collaborator Marius von Mayenburg (directed by Sarah Giles).

version.name: New Electric Ballroom
version.description: Fiendish blarney from Irish Walworth Farce playwright Enda Walsh (directed by Kate Gaul).

version.name: The Brothers Size
version.description: Written by third-year Yale University student Tarell Alvin McCraney, this play transposes West African folklore into America's Deep South (directed by Imara Savage).

version.name: Smashed
version.description: On the Australian side of things, Clare Watson will (not for the first time) direct a tale of childhood and time travel, Smashed, a play from the frankly twisted imagination of Lally Katz.

version.name: Celtic Woman
version.description: For the first time ever, the multi-platinum Irish singing sensations (ocalists Lisa Kelly, Chloë Agnew, Lynn Hilary, Alex Sharpe and fiddler Máiréad Nesbitt) play the nation's stadia in support of Songs from the Heart.

version.name: Paramore
version.description: The Kids will be most excited: the Grammy-nominated US pop-emo quintet are coming to our neck of the woods in support of their new album Brand New Eyes.

version.name: Gorillaz
version.description:
Which actual humans are coming down our way remains a tantalising mystery at the moment (aside from Damon Albarn, one presumes…), but rest assured that Murdoc, 2D, Noodle and Russel will be represented.
Gorillaz from gladiator on Vimeo.

version.name: Creedence Clearwater Revisited
version.description: The Fogerty brothers may be long gone, but the original Creedence Clearwater Revival rhythm section of Stu Cook and Doug "Cosmo" Clifford lead this new band in a selection of their old hits.

version.name: Robin Williams - Weapons of Self-Destruction
version.description: So, this is ostensibly the first ever tour for the legendary actor and stand-up comedian, but we know that he actually did a secret, unannounced show at the Sugarmill in February, so this is technically his follow up, right? Umbilical Brothers are on opening duties.

version.name: Sydney Kings
version.description: The Sydney Kings are backed and ticket sales for season passes close on May 31. Get in now and get ready for their first home game on October 16.

version.name: Pat Benatar and The Bangles
version.description: A reminder girl power was around long befor the Spice Girls.

version.name: Chicago, America and Peter Frampton
version.description: 120 years worth of combined experience takes to the stage for an epichHardcore soft rock show.

version.name: Catcall Launch
version.description: Sydney's own Catherine Kelleher, aka Catcall, returns from a hiatus to launch haunting deep disco track Swimming Pool - her first single since 2008's critically acclaimed Anniversary.

version.name: Alexisonfire
version.description: They can't stop touring in support of their Old Crows Young Cardinals, can they? They're back, they're likely to be in loud form, and it's a licensed all ages show.

version.name: UNSW Oktoberfest 2010
version.description: UNSW's Oktoberfest is a rite of passage for Sydney students and is well known as the city’s best annual uni party. This year the Roundhouse will host 5000 students, 20 bands & DJs, 5 stages and 7 bars. Headline acts include Ian Carey (USA), The Jezabels, Jonathan Boulet, Watussi, Snob Scrilla Sound System, Tom Piper and Andy Murphy.

version.name: Ben Quilty
version.description: Paintings of Captain Cook, morphing into the artist, his son and a skull; exploring masculine lineage.

version.name: David Stephenson: Light Cities
version.description: Stephenson's photographs of cities at night bring together a number of his interests that include the idea of the sublime, environmental concerns, and the transcendental power of light. Light Cities becomes the emblem of so much that is both good and bad in our industrialised culture. Technological awe and human aspiration exist at the same time as the horror of potential environmental catastrophe.

version.name: Catherine O'Donnell: Recent Drawings
version.description: O'Donnell explores the compositional potential and underlying symmetry of urban streetscapes, using artificial light sources or strong directional sunlight to animate buildings, allowing them to reveal their own story.

version.name: Jackin' pres. Joshua Heath
version.description: All the way from the U.S., Joshua Heath is here to kick off the summer season for Jackin’, with a set of body rocking house.

version.name: Musa Dagdeviren at Efendy
version.description: More Turkish spill for this Turkish establishment in Sydney. Musa Dagdeviren is dropping in from Turkey to join forces with Efendy's Somer Sivrioglu where together they will master their culinary skill via the wonders of Turkish taste. A daily seven course sharing menu will be available, changing everyday.

version.name: P.M. Newton - Author Event
version.description: The mysterious sounding P.M. Newton worked in the NSW police force for thirteen years. He launches his debut crime novel 'The Old School'; leaving you to guess what's fiction and what's fact.

version.name: Wylie Dufresne at Bentley
version.description: New York's coolest chef, Wylie Dufresne of wd-50 fame, departs from his residency for the Sydney International Food Festival. For four nights he will collaborate with Bentley's Brent Savage in an eight course degustation. As chef of the New York restaurant that was ranked 45 on the San Pellegrino World's 50 Best Restaurants list, this is an exclusive Sydney event that food lovers would not want to miss.

version.name: The Battle of Waterloo
version.description: A British and a French menu will fight it out at Verandah Bar on 13 Oct in a culinary tribute to the 1815 battle. It appropriately befits the Sydney International Food Festival, host of this unique evening.

version.name: The Australian Beer Festival
version.description: The Australian Heritage Hotel will overflow with beer in October when they host the 6th Annual Australian Beer Festival. Sample boutique Aussie and Kiwi beers, have a say in the People’s Choice Best Beer Award, listen to live music and learn all about brewing.

event.name: Vintage Clothing, Jewellery and Textiles Show

version.name: Vintage Clothing, Jewellery and Textiles Show
version.description: Grab a pre-loved, unique and chic bargain.

version.name: Circo Loco
version.description: One of the best Ibiza clubs is joining forces with Wham! and Redlight to throw a summer shindig. DJs include Jamie Jones, Davide Squillace, Robert Dietz and more.

event.name: Coopers food and beer matching dinner

version.name: Coopers food and beer matching dinner
version.description: Glenn Cooper matches three courses up with seven premium beers from the Coopers range.

version.name: O Magnum Mysterium
version.description: The Sydney Chamber Choir sings 20th Century Christmas classics, plus a new work by Gordon Kerry.

version.name: Parramasala
version.description: Colourful and uplifting, this new festival features a rich innovative program. Today’s most celebrated contemporary artists in music, dance, theatre, film and visual arts will contribute to this celebration of Australia’s most culturally diverse city, Parramatta.

event.name: Roses in the Lumber Yard Heritage Rose Festival

version.name: Roses in the Lumber Yard Heritage Rose Festival
version.vendor-category: Around Town | Fairs & Festivals | Classes, Workshops & talks
version.description: Listen to talks by old tools expert Ralf Hawkins, rose expert Gillian Batchen and park curator Verena Mauldon, try your hand at sustainable gardening with Adrian Bligh or relax in the garden and take in the festival's jazz band over a picnic.

version.name: Markets by Moonlight
version.description: Every Friday night, meander through the Rocks' cobbled streets and pick up a hand-crafted bargain while listening to live musical acts.

version.name: Australian Cheese Showcase 2010
version.description: Sydney's first-ever Australian cheese dedicated market sees producers from NSW and interstate come together at The Rocks Market to show off their cheeses and other cheese-related products.

version.name: Australian International Motor Show
version.description: Sydney plays host to the hottest new cars in the world for a short time only.

version.name: Jim Davidson
version.description: Jim Davidson is firmly established as one of Britain’s top stand-up comedians and the host of BBC TV game shows Generation Game and Big Break. He is bringing his comedy show back to Australia after last years tour for another bite at the apple. Kids be warned, this is an 18+ event.

version.name: Soundwave 2011
version.description: The second and final line up announcement for Soundwave boasts Zach de al Rocha's new project One Day As A Lion, Millencolin, Bullet for my Valentine, Bring Me The Horizon, Murderdolls, Coheed & Cambria, The Amity Affliction and the first ever visit by Dimmu Borger, to name the highlights. They join Iron Maiden, Slayer, Gang of Four, Slash, Queens of the Stone Age, Slayer, Primus, Social Distortion, Rob Zombie, Avenged Sevenfold, Stone Sour, Pennywise, Sum 41, Third Eye Blind, Monster Magnet, The Gaslight Anthem, High on Fire, I See Stars, Nonpoint, Breathe Carolina, 36 Crazyfists, The Bronx, Alesana, 30 Seconds to Mars, Kylesa, Bayside, Asking Alexandria, The Sword, A Skylit Drive, Mad Caddies, There For Tomorrow, Veara, Less than Jake, All That Remains, Trash Talk, The Ataris, Protest The Hero and The Blackout. Whooo!

event.name: Spain meets Japan with Izakaya Dining

version.name: Spain meets Japan with Izakaya Dining
version.description: Guzzle five different sakes picked to match a whopping eight courses of Spanish-Japanese fusion.

event.name: Mehmet Gurs and Phil Wood at Rockpool

version.name: Mehmet Gurs and Phil Wood at Rockpool
version.description: Rockpool is being taken on a sensory journey to the middle East when Phil Wood is joined by Mehmet Gurs of Mikla and Numnum restaurants in Istanbul for the Sydney International Food Festival. For one unique night, head to Rockpool for a Turkish infused culinary indulgence.

event.name: A taste of the South of France at La Grillade

version.name: A taste of the South of France at La Grillade
version.description: French, French, French. Everything is French this evening from the degustation menu and matching wines to the sonic accompaniment for the night. Because what's the Sydney International Food Festival without a night that is tous les Français. And we love a fixed price; $160 will see you through.

version.name: Sirens Big Band
version.description: The all-girl jazz ensemble makes a welcome return appearance after their ABC Jazz-recorded debut in May.

event.name: Steve Clisby and Bill Risby Band

version.name: Steve Clisby and Bill Risby Band
version.description: Steve Clisby is a well traveled vocalist, born in California, lived in Amsterdam, and now singing in Sydney. Clisby has worked across all genres, from Aussie Hip Hop, to RnB, and of course, the Sydney jazz scene.

version.name: Tina Harrod Quartet
version.description: The greatest jazz voice in Sydney takes flight at the Lounge

version.name: Arrebato Ensemble
version.description: The MusicOz Best World Artist winners showcase material from their forthcoming CD over two nights.

version.name: Mike Nock Trio 70th
version.description: The 70th birthday of the internationally-acclaimed jazz pianist and band leader Mike Nock is being celebrated with this special show featuring his trio plus special guests tenor saxophonist Karl Laskowski and guitarist James Muller.

version.name: Jeremy Sawkins Jazz Organism
version.description: Local jazz guitarist Sawkins launches his new CD with a special version of his Organsim.

version.name: The World According To James
version.description: Trombone maestro and band leader James Greening brings his latest ensemble to the Sound Lounge.

version.name: Hola Mexican Film Festival
version.description: The best of recent cinema from Mexico.

version.name: Bathurst 1000 V8 Supercars
version.description: Mt Panorama, Bathurst- the 'Mecca of Motorsport'. Watch the V8 Supercars come alive again with this must-see event.

event.name: Kirsten Fredericks and Sarah Howell - Adam and Eve

version.name: Kirsten Fredericks and Sarah Howell - Adam and Eve
version.description: Sydney and London-based artists Kirsten Fredericks and Sarah Howell explore the holiest of power couples in their first joint exhibition. The works will explore a perverse take on the masculine and feminine, the playfulness of sex and kitsch animals.

version.name: Sculpture By The Sea 2010
version.vendor-category: Around Town | Attractions | Walks, tours & gardens
version.description: Unique artworks pretty up the already breathtaking coastline for 18 days only.

version.name: Sculpture by the Sea 2010
version.vendor-category: Around Town | Walks, tours & gardens | Attractions
version.description: Unique artworks pretty up the already breathtaking coastline for 18 days only.

event.name: Paul Kelly - Book Talk and Musical Performance

version.name: Paul Kelly - Book Talk and Musical Performance
version.description: Paul Kelly's music has had a lasting impact in Australian popular culture. Now Paul has written a book, 'How to Make Gravy', that explores the genesis of many of his greatest songs. Paul will be appearing to talk about the book and perform some acoustic renditions of his songs live.

version.name: Jason "Rash" Ryder
version.description: With 20 years experience in the world of all things funny, this true blue comic is hitting the Laugh Garage stage. Catch him for three nights at one of Sydney's premier comedy spots.

version.name: Matt Okine
version.description: Discovered by Rove in 2007, Matt Okine has since been carving out a name for himself as another of the frighteningly young and talented comics to emerge of late.

version.name: Bev Killick
version.description: Bev Killick's comedy has been likened to Bette Midler,Joan Rivers and Jenny Eclair. A regular on the Australian comedy circuit and a common sight on your TV, you can catch this comedienne at the Laugh garage.

version.name: Balmain Art and Craft Show
version.description: The 15th annual show, featuring three studios with all manner of arts and crafts.

event.name: Alan Jones and Wayde Owen: Cultural Imperialism

version.name: Alan Jones and Wayde Owen: Cultural Imperialism
version.description: Wayde Owen and Alan Jones make an artistic analysis on Australia's colonial past. Owen draws on the history of colonialism in other countries while Jones uses Robert Forrester, his First Fleet ancestor as inspiration for drawings and sculptures.

version.name: Sydney Food and Wine Fair 2010
version.description: Sample wine and treats from the city's best restaurants in Hyde Park's verdant surrounds.

version.name: Night Noodle Markets 2010
version.description: Come nightfall for the period stretching from 11-23 October, Hyde Park will be transformed into a bustling Asian noodle market. This year's market will be bigger than ever with over 40 food stalls, three bars and a beer garden. There will also be a Middle-Eastern themed area within the markets.

version.name: Parade
version.description: The harrowing story of a Jewish man wrongly accused of rape in America's Deep South at a time of civil war.

version.name: Peats Ridge 2010
version.description: The first line up announcement for Peats Ridge is, frankly, a doozy. Brace yourself, music fans, because you're going to be spending New Years in the company of Angus & Julia Stone, Trentemøller (live), Built to Spill, Freestylers, Kate Miller-Heidke, Shout Out Louds, The Dynamites featuring Charles Walker, Born Ruffians, Lightspeed Champion, PVT, Decoder Ring, The Audreys, The Break, Washington, Cloud Control, Jonathan Boulet, Freq Nasty, Space Invadas, The Jezabels, Dan Mangan, Thundamentals, Steve Poltz, Joel Plaskett, King Tide, Horrorshow, Watussi, Parades, Big Scary, Spit Syndicate, Belles Will Ring, Kim Churchill, THE Chemist, The Gin Club, Tom Fun Orchestra, Carmen Townsend, Matt Barber, Chase the Sun, The Lovetones, THE E.L.F, The Seabellies, McCartney, The Delta Riggs, Holly Martin, Spooky Land, Alter Ego Mania, Dereb the Ambassador and The Strides, with loads more artists yet to be announced. Tickets are on sale now, so get a move on if you want to be spending four perfect days of music, art, comedy, theatre and more over the New Years break in the gorgeous surrounds of Glenworth Valley..

version.name: George Calombaris and Gary Mehigan
version.description: Its time for the MasterChef judges to put their money where their mouths are. Escorting readers into their own kitchens, both at work and at home, Calombaris and Mehigan demonstrate the skills, tricks and family favourites they have developed over their culinary careers with 43 of their favourite ingredients made into 86 delicious recipes. Selected recipes from the book will be served on the night so you can get a chance to judge the judges.

version.name: Greek Film Festival 2010
version.description: The 17th annual festival features a diverse programme of Hellenic film.

version.name: Rebel Sport Run4Fun 2010
version.description: The inaugural Rebel Sport Run4Fun is back. The 10km run starts at 9am so the earlier you arrive, the closer you will be placed to the front the start group. Spectators will be allowed to enter ANZ Stadium from 8.30am. There will also be breakfast facilities available.

event.name: Sydney Telstra 500 with Guns n' Roses

version.name: Sydney Telstra 500 with Guns n' Roses
version.description: Axl Rose and his band of hired guns hits Olympic Park as headliner of the V8 Supercars Sydney Telstra 500 weekend.

event.name: Swag Fest with Fabolous and Mario

version.name: Swag Fest with Fabolous and Mario
version.description: Hip-hop and r'n'b fans, rejoice: Fabolous, Step Up star Mario, Phinesse, Surreal, Urban Empire, Peter Gunz, Kay Z and DJ Ace NYC make up the line-up for the first ever Swag Fest. It's all-ages too (although under 18s aren't permitted on the dancefloor).

version.name: Ramsay Health Care Triathlon Pink
version.description: Ramsay Health Care's multi-location triathlon series is run solely for female participants, raising funds for the National Breast Cancer Foundation. There are short, medium and long courses to suit all fitness levels, plus a mini version for the kids.

event.name: Exploring organic and sustainable Chinese food

version.name: Exploring organic and sustainable Chinese food
version.description: For one night only a collaboration is being made between Margaret Yu Xuan of Hong Kong's Kitchen YinYang and Andy Evans from Spice Temple. The Chinese star chef is bringing her expertise to the Sydney International Food Festival to cook up a six course dinner and present the organic and sustainable potential of Chinese food.

event.name: The Animals and Children Took to the Streets

version.name: The Animals and Children Took to the Streets
version.description: Set in a tenement block in a dystopian city, a beast is on the loose and its residents are ruled by fear. This is a world where a man’s shadow can grow a tail and the snout of a wolf; where mirrored reflections move out of time; where telephones grow legs and run away; and where the ‘beast’ is always present.

event.name: Wine with food or food with wine?

version.name: Wine with food or food with wine?
version.description: The rather confused title of this event notifies the power struggle between the food and wine of the evening. And even though our expectations are now flying through the roof, this unique night at Tastevin night, where the wine and food are just as important as each other, is worth a try thanks to five courses and plenty of booze.

version.name: Maggie Alderson - Author Event
version.description: Join columnist and fashion commentator Maggie Alderson for the launch of her latest novel, Shall We Dance?.

version.name: Mirah
version.description: For the first time ever - EVER - US indie folk chanteuse Mirah comes to Australia, joined by The Smallgoods and Shiver Me Timbers, in support of last year's beautiful (A)spera.

version.name: Ottoman Love
version.description: Journey through the Persian Empire with performances from local independent artists and belly dancers. Pass around fruit flavoured Turkish pipes while the mystical fortune teller depicts your destiny.

version.name: Emma Davis - Album Launch
version.description: Emma Davis' songs are a balm for a bruised heart. They are sad songs written by a happy person with a fondness for knobbly jumpers. If you are not completely smitten with the English born songstress by the end of her show then it's entirely likely that you are in fact a robot.

version.name: Perry Keyes
version.description: Three nights: three albums. Mr Keyes will perform his entire ouvre in full, starting with Meter on Thu 7, The Last Ghost Train Home on Fri 8 and the rightly-acclaimed Johnny Ray's Downtown on Sat 9. And he'll be throwing in some other songs as he goes too, with special guests helping out.

version.name: Dastardly Deeds Discussion Panel
version.description: Authors Peter Corris, Malcolm Knox and Kathryn Fox talk about the stabs and blows of crime-writing. Free for members, bookings essential.

version.name: Shaping Inspiration
version.description: An exhibition of drawings, paintings, prints, sculptures and textiles. Meet the artists in their studios and see how and where they work as they give form to their inspiration in the Lennox Street Studios Annual Art Fair.

version.name: Rosebud's mezze nights
version.description: A six course Middle Eastern feast will take place at Rosebud of the inner west during the Sydney International Food Festival. The 50 years of experience that owners mother Camellia has had in the fare is sure to whisk this small restaurant up in to the aromas and flavours of the an authentic Middle Eastern experience. Joining head chef Shane Ryder, a six course menu is on the cards and to tip it off, the legendary Adriano Zumbo will be catering to the sweet teeth for the evening.

version.name: Opera In The Caves
version.description: The Jenolan Caves is soon to be transformed into the Opera House of the Blue Mountains as part of a bold new concept in operatic performance.

version.name: Opera in the Vineyards
version.description: A journey through the life and times of Mozart's musical genius, led by performers in full period costume in surrounds of the vineyards.

version.name: Halloween Festival 2010
version.description: Get spooked at this year's Halloween Festival held on the grounds of Nicholson Street Public School for children, parents and locals. Kids can head for monstrous rides like the Dinosaur Predator Slide, get ghouled at the Witch's Cauldron, sweeten up with the Chocolate Wheel or go head-to-head in the Pumpkin Toss competition. Parents will be kept entertained with the jack-o'-lantern auction and drinkable treats from the Kitchen of Horror.

version.name: Open Arms Festival
version.description: Coffs Harbour is the latest beachside town to announce a music festival, with Open Arms taking over on Sat 20 Nov with a genre-mixing line-up that includes The Living End, Birds of Tokyo, Grafton Primary, Hungry Kids of Hungary, Horrorshow, Behind Crimson Eyes, City Riots and Metals, with further acts to be announced. Earlybird tickets are on sale now, so get a move on if you want to save some dollars.

event.name: Why the Mind Experiences Hope and Doubt

version.name: Why the Mind Experiences Hope and Doubt
version.description: The 7th Dzogchen Rinpoche, one of the most important living Tibetan Buddhists, will give a a talk on the pitfalls of hope and happiness.

version.name: Laneway Festival
version.description: Mark it in your diary, kids: the first line-up announcement is a little while off yet, but this is the confirmed date'n'location for Laneway 2011.

version.name: A Midsummer Night' Dream
version.description: Bring a picnic and a rug for the inaugural Shakespeare in the Rose Garden, starring some of Australia’s finest young actors. This production promises to be a passionate, honest and original staging of this classic play.

version.name: Barolo v barbaresco
version.description: A showcase of two of the world's greatest wines accompanied by a delicious Piemontese feast.

event.name: Mikey Robins and Darren Simson do Italy

version.name: Mikey Robins and Darren Simson do Italy
version.description: These two chefs present 5 courses with matching wine at La Scala for the Sydney International Food Festival. Diving head first in to the overwhelming nature of Italy, they will be serving up passion vigor and a maybe even a touch of romance for a bellissimo evening.

version.name: Cooking Class with Armando Percuoco
version.description: Buon Ricordo's Armando Percuoco and Massimo Mele of Hugo's Manly teach a one-off Italian cooking class just in time for the silly season.

version.name: Cooking Class with Janni Kyritsis
version.description: Janni Kyritsis joins Jonathan Barthelmess of new Italian haunt Manly Pavilion for a mediterranean cooking adventure: 'Venetian Empire Influence on the Greek Islands'.

version.name: Connections
version.description: Islamic works of art in dialogue with other items in the national art collection under themes such as calligraphy, geometry, colour and the garden. An exploration of connections across cultures, place and time.

version.name: Anton Bruehl photographs 1920s–1950s
version.description: The photographic work of South Australian-born Anton Bruehl, the creative force behind one of the most inventive New York photographic studios of the early 20th century - a true 'Mad Man' before the time documented in the HBO series.

version.name: Curries from Around the World
version.description: Learn to make Thai, Indian and Middle Eastern curries, with plenty of exotic spices and flavours.

version.name: Frolic at the Polo
version.description: Enjoy three action-packed games, flowing bubbles, yummy food and glamorous frocks at this Spring polo event.

version.name: FBi's Still Life 2010
version.description: Still Life is an art auction aimed at stimulating Sydney's artistic centre and raising some much-needed funds for FBi radio, featuring works from a range of established and emerging Sydney artists.

version.name: Marie Antoinette
version.description: Sofia Coppola's adaptation of the story of one of France's most famous ladies will appeal to film buff and teenagers alike.

version.name: Children Of Paradise
version.description: Made during the dying days of WWII, this film follows a strong and independent woman as she is pursued by various suitors.

version.name: The Crimson Curtain
version.description: This 1952 French classic revolves around a young soldier who is billeted with a middle class family and begins an affair with their beautiful daughter.

version.name: Les Miserables
version.description: Undoubtedly one of the most famous French stories ever told, this ambitious film version was made in 1933

version.name: The Devil On Two Sticks
version.description: This 1948 films tells the story of Charles-Maurice, Prince of Tallyerand, who was a shrewd political operator in late 18th century France.

version.name: Don't Touch The Axe
version.description: A Parisian coquette risks her marriage and societal standing when she pursues an intriguing French general back from the war in this film set in the 1820s.

version.name: Time Out Sydney Bar Awards 2011
version.description: You know the nominees - but who will win on this night of nights?

version.name: Paul Cunningham at Astral
version.description: Flying in from Denmark for the Sydney International Food Festival is British-born Paul Cunningham. Taking his experimental style from the award winning Copenhagan kitchen, The Paul, he is compiling a six course degustationa at Astral.

version.name: Journey to Jamaica
version.description: Escape to the Caribbean at Signorelli Gastronomia for one night as it transforms in to a Jamaican paradise. Sip on Rum cocktails while you chill to reggae music. The menu will include typically Jamaican dishes from salt cod to jerk chicken thanks to the restaurant's sous chef, Damion Brown. Ya man.

version.name: Brown Brothers - expect the unexpected
version.description: Focusing on local and sustainable produce, this three-course meal is accompanied by a special selection of limited release wines.

version.name: Comedy Unleashed
version.description:
Get ready to have your ribs tickled as actress Holly Brisley brings together some of the biggest names in Australian stand up. Hilarity in the form of Heath Franklin's Chopper, Akmal Saleh, Peter Berner and many more will be stepping up to the stage in the shinily refitted surrounds of Le Montage.
Laughing make you hungry? Then opt for the dinner and show package. Got no sense of humour? Then just tuck in and enjoy the spectacular views, because it's all for a good cause. The event supports the outstanding work of the Humpty Dumpty foundation which ensures that children throughout NSW and East Timor have access to medial equipment and services.
